module AffineMention

(* THE RULE (PROVE.md §7, settled here): naming an affine binding in a predicate
   is a MENTION, not a USE.  Predicates are use-neutral — they never consume.
   
   Buf is NOT Copy, so `b` is affine: the control below shows the checker really
   does count uses.  Yet `b` appears in take's precondition `v < size(b)` AND is
   used once in take's body, and that is fine.  It is fine by construction, not by
   a special case: refinements erase in syntype_to_mono before inference ever
   traverses them, so a predicate cannot increment a use count.
   
   Why it is sound: affinity in Lark restricts USE, not TRUTH.  Lark is pure, so
   consuming a value moves it, it does not mutate it — a fact proved about an
   affine binding stays true for the whole scope.  In a language with mutation the
   rule would be unsound.  The permission is paid for by purity and nothing else. *)

type Buf = | Buf of Int

fn size(b: Buf) : Int =
  match b with | Buf(n) => n end

fn take(b: Buf, i: {v: Int | v >= 0 and v < size(b)}) : Int =
  match b with | Buf(n) => n + i end
